1
00:00:00 --> 00:00:08
So let's try to bring together two things that at first glance have absolutely nothing to do with each other. Napoleon's military campaigns and the great masterpieces of Italian opera.

2
00:00:08 --> 00:00:18
Seems strange, right? On one hand, we have war, strategy, gunpowder, and on the other, arias, scenography, and great passions on stage.

3
00:00:18 --> 00:00:25
And yet this is the incredible part: there is a surprising chain of events that indissolubly links war to art.

4
00:00:25 --> 00:00:35
So the question we ask ourselves today is exactly this, it almost seems like a paradox, a riddle of history. Well, let's go discover, based on very interesting research,

5
00:00:35 --> 00:00:44
how a change imposed by the force of arms gave rise, almost by chance, to one of the most brilliant and productive eras in music history.

6
00:00:44 --> 00:00:51
To understand this revolution, however, we have to take a step back. It's the end of the 18th century. Opera in Italy is hugely popular, a true national craze.

7
00:00:51 --> 00:00:58
But for those who created it, that is the composers, life was anything but simple.

8
00:00:58 --> 00:01:05
They lived in a system that today we would define as total precarity. Here, we see the problem in black and white.

9
00:01:05 --> 00:01:12
Before 1801, a composer was paid only once for an entire opera, a one-off payment and that's it.

10
00:01:12 --> 00:01:20
It didn't matter if the opera was a fiasco or a resounding success with hundreds of performances; economically, nothing changed for him.

11
00:01:20 --> 00:01:27
And as if that weren't enough, piracy was the norm; his scores were copied and sold freely, and he didn't see a cent.

12
00:01:27 --> 00:01:36
And this frustration wasn't just economic, it was also artistic. This phrase, attributed to a giant like Rossini, says it all.

13
00:01:36 --> 00:01:41
When he felt he was being paid too little, he practically threatened to recycle his own music.

14
00:01:41 --> 00:01:48
And who can blame him? Why invest time and energy to create something completely new, something memorable,

15
00:01:48 --> 00:01:55
if the system doesn't reward you for long-term success? There was no real incentive to create masterpieces.

16
00:01:55 --> 00:02:03
And then suddenly chaos arrives, or rather Napoleon arrives. His Italian campaign wasn't just a military event,

17
00:02:03 --> 00:02:13
but it transformed, without anyone having planned it, into a giant social and economic experiment. An experiment that, in fact, would change the rules of the game forever.

18
00:02:13 --> 00:02:17
And here we come to the key point of the whole story.

19
00:02:17 --> 00:02:23
The Napoleonic armies didn't just bring cannons and soldiers but also codes and laws.

20
00:02:23 --> 00:02:33
And among these, an absolutely revolutionary law on copyright. But there is a fundamental catch: this law was not applied everywhere.

21
00:02:33 --> 00:02:43
And this patchy application created a sharp divide in the peninsula. Let's look at the sequence of events: 1796, the invasion begins.

22
00:02:43 --> 00:02:51
A few years pass and in 1801, the new copyright law is introduced in the Cisalpine Republic, which effectively included Lombardy and Veneto.

23
00:02:51 --> 00:03:00
Only later, in 1804, the famous Napoleonic Civil Code was extended to other territories. But that code, unlike the previous law,

24
00:03:00 --> 00:03:08
did not include copyright protection. So, suddenly, Italy found itself divided in two. Territories with and territories without copyright.

25
00:03:08 --> 00:03:15
And what happens when rules are changed so drastically? Well, the first consequence, the most immediate one,

26
00:03:15 --> 00:03:22
is that the activity of composers moves en masse toward the areas where their works are protected.

27
00:03:22 --> 00:03:33
Between 1801 and 1820, the production of new operas in territories that had adopted copyright was about double that of those that hadn't.

28
00:03:33 --> 00:03:38
But it's not just a matter of quantity. This is where the study becomes truly fascinating.

29
00:03:38 --> 00:03:45
Researchers analyzed the quality of these works by following a very specific indicator.

30
00:03:45 --> 00:03:51
How many of these works are still performed today? The famous immortal masterpieces.

31
00:03:51 --> 00:04:03
And guess what? The probability that a work would become a lasting success increased drastically if the author knew they could count on royalties.

32
00:04:03 --> 00:04:11
Quite simply, one starts producing more where it's most convenient to do so. But the story doesn't end here; on the contrary.

33
00:04:11 --> 00:04:18
Because while it's true that quantity is important, for art, the real challenge is quality.

34
00:04:18 --> 00:04:24
How is it possible that a law on rights influences creativity itself?

35
00:04:24 --> 00:04:33
Well, the answer lies in incentives. With copyright, the work stops being a disposable product and becomes an asset, an income for the future.

36
00:04:33 --> 00:04:42
Imagine you are a composer. If you know that every time your work is staged you will receive a commission,

37
00:04:42 --> 00:04:54
you'll have every interest in the world to write something so beautiful, so innovative, and so powerful that people will want to hear it again and again for decades.

38
00:04:54 --> 00:05:02
In practice, copyright created the conditions for composers to stop thinking like daily craftsmen

39
00:05:02 --> 00:05:07
and start thinking like real creators of value over time.

40
00:05:07 --> 00:05:14
And the data confirm this theory. Works born under copyright protection had a much higher probability,

41
00:05:14 --> 00:05:25
about 25% more, of entering the standard repertoire and staying there for centuries. Masterpieces like those of Rossini, or later Verdi,

42
00:05:25 --> 00:05:36
were not just the result of isolated strokes of genius, but also of an economic environment that finally rewarded excellence and artistic longevity.

43
00:05:36 --> 00:05:44
All this leads us to a deeper reflection. We often think of art and economics as two separate worlds,

44
00:05:44 --> 00:05:49
one made of pure inspiration, the other of cold calculations and regulations.

45
00:05:49 --> 00:05:55
But the history of Italian opera teaches us that it's not like that. In fact, it's quite the opposite.

46
00:05:55 --> 00:06:03
It is only when we gave inspiration a solid legal basis and economic protection

47
00:06:03 --> 00:06:10
that genius could truly take flight and create something immortal.

48
00:06:10 --> 00:06:16
Point one: the law guaranteed composers would earn from every single performance of their work.

49
00:06:16 --> 00:06:28
Point two: this created a powerful incentive to no longer write disposable music, but to aim for successes that lasted over time.

50
00:06:28 --> 00:06:43
And point three: this new economic stability gave them the most precious thing they didn't have before: time, time and resources to dedicate more care and attention to each individual composition.

51
00:06:43 --> 00:06:52
A legal change, a real accident of history brought by Napoleon's wars, completely redesigned the market for creativity.

52
00:06:52 --> 00:06:59
It aligned for the first time the economic interests of composers with the public's desire for unforgettable works.

53
00:06:59 --> 00:07:05
In practice, it created the fertile ground, the economic conditions for the birth of immortal masterpieces.

54
00:07:05 --> 00:07:11
And all this leads us to a final question that links that distant world to ours.

55
00:07:11 --> 00:07:20
The history of opera teaches us that art is never born in a vacuum; it's always influenced by the economic, legal, and technological structures surrounding it.

56
00:07:20 --> 00:07:31
So, it's natural to wonder, what are today's historical accidents or technological revolutions, perhaps those we are living through without even realizing it,

57
00:07:31 --> 00:07:38
that are silently shaping the music, cinema, or literature of the future?

58
00:07:38 --> 00:07:44
That's all for today. If you liked this video and want to discover other incredible stories that link economics to our daily lives,

59
00:07:44 --> 00:07:51
don't forget to subscribe to the channel. We'll see you again soon for a new jump into history and economics.

60
00:07:51 --> 00:07:58
Thanks for following us and see you next time.